<setup>
  <selectFromSequence name="h" from="3" to="5" step="1"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="k" from="-2" to="2" step="1" exclude="0"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="z1" from="1" to="2" step="1"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="z2" from="1" to="2" step="1" exclude="$z1"/>
  <math name="x1" simplify>$h - $z1</math>
  <math name="x2" simplify>$h + $z2</math>
  <math name="y1" simplify>$$f($x1)</math>
  <math name="y2" simplify>$$f($x2)</math>
  <math name="m" simplify>($y2-$y1)/($x2-$x1)</math>
  <selectFromSequence name="a1" from="1" to="1" step="2"/>
  <function name="f" styleNumber="1"> $a1*((x-$h)^2+$k)</function>
  <function name="g" styleNumber="2"> $a1*($m*(x - $x1) + $y1)</function>
  
  <math name="intValue" simplify>abs(1/3*($x2-$h)^3 + $k*$x2 - $m/2*($x2-$x1)^2 - $y1*$x2 - (1/3*($x1-$h)^3 + $k*$x1 - $m/2*($x1-$x1)^2 - $y1*$x1)) </math>

</setup>  

  <p>
    Consider the functions given by
    <me>f(x) = <math simplify>$a1*((x-$h)^2+$k)</math> , \ g(x) = <math simplify>$a1*(($y2-$y1)/($x2-$x1)*(x - $x1) + $y1)</math></me>
  </p>


<!--
<graph size="medium" xmin="-1" xmax="7" ymin="-4" ymax="4" showNavigation="false" fixAxes="true">
  $f
  $g
</graph>  

<p>
  <m>x_1 = $x1, x_2 = $x2, y_1 = $y1, y_2 = $y2, </m>
</p>  
-->


  <p> 
    <ol marker="a.">
      <li>
        <p>
          Plot <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> and use the graph or algebra to find the exact points of intersection between <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>.  State each intersection point as an ordered pair in the space below; if there is more than one, separate them with commas.
        </p>
        <p><answer><mathList unordered>($x1,$y1) ($x2,$y2)</mathList></answer></p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Find an integral expression that represents the area between
          <m>y = f(x)</m> and <m>y = g(x)</m> on the interval between their intersection points of <m>f</m> and <m>g</m>.  Once you identify the lower and upper limits of integration, those numbers will appear in the integral expression below.
        </p>

        <p>
          lower limit of integration: <m>a = </m> <answer name="a">$x1</answer>
        </p>
        <p>
          upper limit of integration: <m>b = </m> <answer name="b">$x2</answer>
        </p>

        <p>
          Integral expression for area, <m>A</m> between <m>y = f(x)</m> and the <m>y = g(x)</m>: 
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>A = \displaystyle\int_{$a}^{$b}</m><mathInput name="int1" minWidth="100" /><m>dx \,</m><answer><award><when>($$f($h) > $$g($h) and $int1 = $f - $g) or ($$f($h) < $$g($h) and $int1 = $g - $f) </when></award></answer> <!--, <m>$$f($h), $$g($h), $f - $g</m> -->
        </p> 
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Evaluate the integral exactly to find the numerical value of the area, <m>A</m>, between <m>y = f(x)</m> and <m>y = g(x)</m>, on the interval between their intersection points, and report the value below. 
        </p>
        <p>
          <m>A = </m><mathInput name="intVal" minWidth="40" /> <answer><award><when>$intValue=$intVal </when></award></answer>
        </p>  
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>